================================================================
PRACTICAL 10(b) - Automate Any Process Using State Machine in UiPath
================================================================

DIFFICULTY: Hard

WHAT YOU WILL DO:
You will build a simple vending machine simulation using 
State Machine in UiPath.

States:
  State 1: Idle         → waiting for user input
  State 2: Processing   → processing the selection
  State 3: Dispensing   → giving the item
  Final State: Done

--- WHAT IS A STATE MACHINE? ---
  A State Machine is a type of workflow where the automation can 
  be in one of several STATES at any time.
  Transitions between states happen based on CONDITIONS.
  Each state has Entry and Exit actions.

--- STEP-BY-STEP INSTRUCTIONS ---

Step 1: Open UiPath Studio → New Project.
  - Name it: Practical_10b_StateMachine
  - Click Create

Step 2: Delete the default Sequence and select "State Machine" 
        as the root type.
  - In the Designer area, right-click → select "Add Activity" → 
    search "State Machine" and add it.
  OR:
  - Create a new project and in the initial dialog, choose 
    "State Machine" template instead of "Blank Process".

Step 3: You'll see a State Machine canvas. Right-click → 
        "Add State" to add your states.

ADDING STATE 1 - IDLE:

Step 4: Double-click to add a State → rename it "Idle".
  - Double-click the Idle state to open its editor.
  - In the ENTRY section, drag an "Input Dialog" activity.
    - Title: "Vending Machine"
    - Label: "Select item: 1=Water, 2=Juice, 3=Soda"
    - Result: press Ctrl+K → name it: userChoice (type: String)
  - Click the back arrow to return to the State Machine canvas.

ADDING STATE 2 - PROCESSING:

Step 5: Add another state → rename it "Processing".
  - Double-click to open it.
  - In the ENTRY section, drag a "Message Box".
    - Text: "Processing your selection: " + userChoice
  - Click back.

ADDING STATE 3 - DISPENSING:

Step 6: Add another state → rename it "Dispensing".
  - Double-click to open it.
  - In the ENTRY section, drag an "If" activity.
    - Condition: userChoice = "1"
    - THEN: Message Box → Text: "Dispensing Water. Enjoy!"
    - ELSE: 
        Add another If:
        - Condition: userChoice = "2"
        - THEN: Message Box → Text: "Dispensing Juice. Enjoy!"
        - ELSE: Message Box → Text: "Dispensing Soda. Enjoy!"
  - Click back.

ADDING FINAL STATE:

Step 7: Add a "Final State" (there should be a built-in option 
        when you right-click).
  - This ends the State Machine.

ADDING TRANSITIONS (ARROWS):

Step 8: Hover over the Idle state — you'll see a small arrow/handle appear.
  - Drag from Idle → to Processing.
  - A transition line appears. Click on it to edit.
  - Condition: Not String.IsNullOrEmpty(userChoice)
    (i.e., move to Processing only if user entered something)

Step 9: Drag transition from Processing → to Dispensing.
  - Condition: True  (always move after processing)

Step 10: Drag transition from Dispensing → to Final State.
  - Condition: True

Step 11: Set the Initial State:
  - Right-click on "Idle" state → "Set as Initial State"
  - This is where the State Machine starts.

Step 12: Run (F5).
  EXPECTED FLOW:
  1. Input dialog appears (Idle state)
  2. User types "1" → clicks OK
  3. "Processing your selection: 1" message appears
  4. "Dispensing Water. Enjoy!" message appears
  5. State Machine ends.

TIPS:
  - Each state can have ENTRY (runs when you enter the state) 
    and EXIT (runs when you leave the state) sections.
  - Transitions have CONDITIONS — the first true condition fires.
  - State machines are great for workflows with multiple possible 
    paths (like login retry logic, multi-step forms, etc.)

